---
import Base from '#layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '#components/Nav.astro';
import Waitlist from '#components/Waitlist.astro';
import Footer from '#components/Footer.astro';

const categories = [
  {
    title: 'Getting started',
    items: [
      {
        question: 'What is Tmonier?',
        answer:
          'Tmonier is a local-first monitoring daemon for Claude Code. It watches every file change, every command, every dollar spent. It catches loops, scope drift, and context bloat before they waste your time. Checkpoints let you roll back before anything ships.',
      },
      {
        question: 'How does it work?',
        answer:
          'Run tmonier start in your project. A lightweight daemon spawns Claude Code, captures every event — file edits, shell commands, token usage — and streams them to a real-time dashboard. No code leaves your machine.',
      },
      {
        question: 'What does "local-first" mean?',
        answer:
          'The daemon runs entirely on your machine. It observes session metadata — files touched, commands run, token counts — but never reads or stores your source code. The dashboard connects via a local websocket and just streams command output — your codebase stays on your machine.',
      },
      {
        question: 'How do I install Tmonier?',
        answer:
          "Tmonier is currently in private beta. Join the waitlist to get early access — you'll receive install instructions as soon as the beta opens. Installation is a single command.",
      },
      {
        question: 'Which AI tools does Tmonier support?',
        answer:
          'Claude Code at launch. OpenCode (which supports Copilot licenses), Codex CLI, Aider, and Cline are on the roadmap. The architecture is CLI-agnostic by design — if your tool has a CLI, Tmonier can monitor it.',
      },
      {
        question: 'What are the system requirements?',
        answer:
          'macOS or Linux (Windows via WSL). Git installed. Claude Code as your AI CLI. The daemon is lightweight and runs in the background with minimal CPU and memory overhead.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    title: 'Features',
    items: [
      {
        question: 'What does Tmonier monitor in real time?',
        answer:
          'Every file read, created, or edited. Every shell command. Token usage, context window percentage, and running cost. All streamed live to your dashboard as events happen.',
      },
      {
        question: 'What is loop detection?',
        answer:
          'Tmonier detects edit\u2009\u2192\u2009test\u2009\u2192\u2009fail\u2009\u2192\u2009edit cycles where the agent is stuck repeating the same pattern. It flags the loop in your dashboard and suggests a prompt to help the agent break out.',
      },
      {
        question: 'What is scope drift?',
        answer:
          'When your agent starts touching files outside the scope you declared for the task, Tmonier flags it immediately. You see exactly which files were accessed outside scope so you can course-correct before the agent goes further off track.',
      },
      {
        question: 'How does context window monitoring work?',
        answer:
          'A live gauge shows how much of the context window is consumed. At 65%+ Tmonier warns that the agent may start losing early instructions and suggests opening a fresh window from your last checkpoint.',
      },
      {
        question: 'What are checkpoints & rollback?',
        answer:
          'Available on Solo and above. Checkpoints are approval gates that snapshot your project state. If something goes wrong, you roll back to the last clean state and resume with just the necessary context — no reprompting needed.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Can I monitor multiple agents at once?',
        answer:
          'Yes. The Free plan monitors 1 agent. The Solo plan supports up to 5 concurrent agents, each with its own activity stream in the dashboard.',
      },
      {
        question: 'How does cost awareness work?',
        answer:
          'A live cost counter tracks spending in real time. Tmonier hints when a cheaper model would suffice for the current task. On Solo and above, you can set budget guardrails that pause the session before exceeding a threshold.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    title: 'Pricing & plans',
    items: [
      {
        question: 'What does BYOA (Bring Your Own AI) mean?',
        answer:
          "Tmonier never marks up your AI tokens. You pay Claude (or any supported provider) directly at their standard rates. Tmonier only charges for the monitoring layer — there's no hidden per-token fee and no vendor lock-in.",
      },
      {
        question: 'Is the Free plan really free?',
        answer:
          'Yes, forever. The Free plan includes real-time activity monitoring, loop detection, scope drift alerts, and context window tracking for 1 agent. No credit card required, no trial period.',
      },
      {
        question: 'What does the Solo plan add?',
        answer:
          'Checkpoints & rollback, budget guardrails, compaction-proof memory, cost hints, and support for up to 5 monitored agents. \u20AC4.99/mo ($5.99).',
      },
      {
        question: 'What does the Team plan add?',
        answer:
          'A team dashboard with shared visibility across agents, shared guardrails enforced for every team member, and cross-agent conflict detection. \u20AC9.99/seat/mo ($11.99).',
      },
      {
        question: 'Can I switch plans or cancel anytime?',
        answer:
          'Yes, all plans are month-to-month with no lock-in. Upgrade, downgrade, or cancel at any time. If you cancel a paid plan, you keep access through the end of your billing period, then drop to the Free tier.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Why is there no per-token pricing?',
        answer:
          "Because Tmonier is a monitoring layer, not an AI provider. You already pay for tokens through Claude. Adding a per-token fee would create misaligned incentives — we'd profit when your agent uses more tokens, even if that's wasteful. A flat fee keeps us aligned: we succeed when your sessions are efficient.",
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    title: 'Privacy & security',
    items: [
      {
        question: 'Does Tmonier access my source code?',
        answer:
          'No. Tmonier observes session metadata only — file-change counts, token usage, context window percentage, session duration. It never reads, parses, or stores your source code.',
      },
      {
        question: 'What data does Tmonier collect?',
        answer:
          'Token counts, context window utilisation percentages, session durations, file-change counts (not contents), and checkpoint events. Never file contents, diffs, prompts, or AI responses.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Is Tmonier GDPR compliant?',
        answer:
          'Yes. All data is processed and stored in EU-based infrastructure. Enterprise customers get a Data Processing Agreement (DPA) and SOC 2 Type II certification.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Can I self-host Tmonier?',
        answer:
          'Yes, on the Enterprise plan. You deploy Tmonier on your own infrastructure for full control over data residency, access policies, and integration with internal systems.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Does Tmonier work with local models?',
        answer:
          'Ollama support is on our roadmap. Once available, you\u2019ll be able to run fully private coding sessions where everything stays on your machine.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    title: 'How it compares',
    items: [
      {
        question: 'How is Tmonier different from just using Claude Code?',
        answer:
          'Claude Code gives you raw agent output. Tmonier adds a real-time dashboard, loop detection, scope drift alerts, context window monitoring, cost tracking, checkpoints & rollback, and suggested prompts to unblock your agent. It\u2019s the visibility layer that makes Claude Code predictable.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Does Tmonier replace my IDE or terminal?',
        answer:
          'No. Tmonier is an additive monitoring layer that runs alongside your existing tools. You keep using your IDE, terminal, and Claude Code exactly as before. Tmonier just watches and alerts.',
      },
    ],
  },
];
---

<Base title="FAQ — Tmonier" description="Frequently asked questions about Tmonier — the local-first monitoring daemon for Claude Code.">
  <Nav currentPage="faq" />
  <main>
    <!-- Mini hero -->
    <section class="bg-navy-deep" style="padding: 5rem 2.5rem 3rem; text-align: center;">
      <div style="max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <p
          class="font-mono"
          style="font-size: 0.75rem; letter-spacing: 0.15em; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgba(196, 154, 43, 0.6); margin: 0 0 1rem;"
        >
          Questions & answers
        </p>
        <h1
          class="font-vollkorn-sc text-gold"
          style="font-weight: 900; font-size: clamp(2rem, 4.5vw, 3rem); margin: 0 0 1.25rem; line-height: 1.15;"
        >
          Frequently asked questions
        </h1>
        <p
          class="font-source-serif text-slate"
          style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0; max-width: 600px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"
        >
          Everything you need to know about Tmonier — from getting started to privacy and pricing.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ content -->
    <section class="bg-navy-deep" style="padding: 0 2.5rem 5rem;">
      <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">
        {categories.map((category) => (
          <div style="margin-bottom: 3rem;">
            <h2
              class="font-mono"
              style="font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.15em; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgba(196, 154, 43, 0.6); margin: 0 0 1.5rem; padding-bottom: 0.75rem; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(196, 154, 43, 0.15);"
            >
              {category.title}
            </h2>
            {category.items.map((item) => (
              <details class="faq-item">
                <summary class="faq-summary">
                  <span>{item.question}</span>
                </summary>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                  <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                    <p
                      class="font-source-serif text-slate"
                      style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0;"
                    >
                      {item.answer}
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </details>
            ))}
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <Waitlist />
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Base>

<style>
  .faq-item {
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(139, 156, 175, 0.1);
  }

  .faq-summary {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
    padding: 1.25rem 0;
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    font-family: 'Source Serif 4', serif;
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #f5f0e8;
    transition: color 0.2s;
  }

  .faq-summary::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .faq-summary::marker {
    display: none;
    content: '';
  }

  .faq-summary::after {
    content: '+';
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: #c49a2b;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    margin-left: 1rem;
    transition: transform 0.3s ease;
  }

  details[open] > .faq-summary::after {
    content: '\2212';
  }

  .faq-summary:hover {
    color: #c49a2b;
  }

  .faq-answer {
    overflow: hidden;
    max-height: 0;
    transition: max-height 0.4s ease;
  }

  details[open] > .faq-answer {
    max-height: 500px;
  }

  .faq-answer-inner {
    padding: 0 0 1.5rem;
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .faq-summary {
      font-size: 1rem;
      padding: 1rem 0;
    }
  }
</style>
